{"cursor":"12395","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" weight.]]\n\n'Troy weight' is a system of units of mass customarily used for precious metals\nand gemstones. There are 12 troy ounces per troy pound, {{cite book\n| last = Baynes first = Thomas Spencer title = The Encyclopaedia Britannica\n| publisher = H.G. Allen year = 1888 edition = 9th volume = 2 page = 533 url =\n| http://books.google.com/books?id=hakMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA533&dq=%22The+Encyclopaedi-\n| a+Britannica%22+%22weights+and+measures%22&hl=en&ei=PQu_TuegEJPciQKOreCNAw&sa-\n| =X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false\n}} rather than the 16 ounces per pound found in the more common\navoirdupois system. The troy ounce is 480 grains, compared with the avoirdupois\nounce, which is 437Â½ grains. Both systems use the same grain defined by the\ninternational yard and pound agreement of 1959 as exactly\n0.06479891 gram. NIST\n[http://ts.nist.gov/WeightsAndMeasures/Publications/upload/h4402_appenc.pdf\nGeneral Tables of Units of Measurement]. United States government.\nAlthough troy ounces are still used to weigh gold, silver, and gemstones, troy\nweight is no longer used in most other applications.\n","linknr":288,"url":"Troy_weight","recorded":1374523521,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Troy_weight&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Troy_weight&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/